It isn't as much that~birthrates have dropped incredibly in the last 50 years. As a matter of fact some developed countries have TOO low a birthrate. It's much, much more complex. Just 120 years ago, life expectancy was around 46 - 48 years. It's now more than double that. In a century! So way, way fewer people are dying "of their teeth" as was the common verbiage then. We live longer and are much healthier than we were, but some just live longer through medicinal means. Before antibiotics people died of a simple bacterial infection, like strep throat. Before other life saving drugs like insulin, children with type 1 diabetes lived less than five years. Before heart meds allowed for people with heart disease to live longer, it was the most common cause of death. So to say it's the birthrate just doesn't ring true. Because it really, really isn't. My understanding is that a large number of arsonists were caught in Australia and the media doesn't want that known. Many were very young. This was a misrepresentation of the arrests and citations made. While SOME of the fires were believed to have been set deliberately (24 known acts), the vast majority of the arrests made were against individuals who failed to uphold the fire bans being imposed, not deliberate arson. And of the approximately 200 "arrests" some of the charges were merely citations for lighting cooking fires in fire-prone regions while not actually causing the spread of the wildfires. According to the New South Wales police, "53 people have had legal actions for allegedly failing to comply with a total fire ban,” and an additional “47 people have had legal actions for allegedly discarding a lighted cigarette or match on land.” But it's a lot flashier to say that almost 200 counts of arson were committed during Australia's wildfires. Some of those arrests certainly were, but the elements that kept feeding the wildfires were heat and drought, something Australia has been experiencing with increasing regularity. Just an FYI.
